ther larger rooms, and was informed there were no rooms at all and anyway, the rooms were all the same size. Really? So why had I been given an upgrade (at £30 per person per night more!) to an 'executive' disabled friendly family room, and why, oh why, was it so obvious that NONE of the rooms could accommodate a wheelchair? A shrug, and the person I was speaking to began to walk away. It was obvious she didn't give a damn that my family and I were now stranded with no accommodation, despite having travelled over 450 miles from Scotland that day, to stay there.I asked to speak to the management before she left me stranded there, and was told there was no one there to help. At this point, I was actually laughed at by the ignorant and dismissive woman, who said this was 'nothing to do with the hotel at all' - I should complain to the holiday booking agency (LondonBy.com). Use of a telephone to attempt to arrange suitable relocation was refused, and we were left with the option of going it alone to try to get somewhere else that night, or trying to struggle in what had turned out to be a totally overpriced, unsuitable room, with staff who didn't give a damn, and who actually walked away when we pleaded for help.We left, and managed to eventually find a Travelodge, miles away from the hospital we needed to visit the next day in Hampstead, with over 450 miles of exhausting travel extended by another three hours of stress and searching for somewhere else to stay.Minus 10 out of 10 for this place. A completely disgusting attitude from staff, at a hotel absolutely unsuitable for anyone not able to brave dodgy lifts and stairs and who is 100% physically sound. Oh, and if you can't cope with rude and dismissive staff, who laugh at someone who is disabled when you have a major problem to sort out, save yourself some grief and DON'T COME HERE!Quality Hotel?! Surely someone could take THAT completely misleading name up with the help of the Trades Descriptions Act and win their case. Out of interest, you may like to know that my written complaints to management at this hotel remain ignored after two months.I'm leaving this review as true representation of my experience, not as a 'rant'. I'm using this forum as a means to warn other prospective disabled visitors (who might book in good faith and then be as unlucky as my family and I were, on arrival). I wouldn't wish our experience on anyone, let alone someone who is in a wheelchair, and in chronic pain. The experience was a complete nightmare from start to finish. P.S. Incidentally, I have the highest praise and recommendation for the Travelodge at Kew Bridge (which, although well out of our way, was where we were eventually able to find a room). They were most helpful and the room was superb. If you need polite staff, spacious rooms, and somewhere with disabled, family, and pet-friendly attitudes, you could do a lot worse than relocate as we did. 	
